zard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"Abt 1151–":"about 1151–Deceased","1136–1214":"1136–1214","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1174–1234":"1174–1234","1151–Female":"1151–Deceased","1174":"1174","1151":"1151","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","Abt 1151":"about 1151","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1214":"1214","1169":"1169","1224":"1224","1136":"1136","1234":"1234","about 1174":"about 1174","Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Merton, Merton, Surrey, England":"Merton, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England":"Weston under Lizard, Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Surrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the county of Surrey, from Old English <i>sūther</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>gē</i> ‘district, region’, possibly a reference to its position south of the Thames."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":64,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":73,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":108,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Maud of Surrey was born about 1151, in Surrey, England. She married Hamon de Weston in 1169, in Merton, Surrey, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"Abt 1151–":"umbes 1151–Surnud","1136–1214":"1136–1214","1169–1227":"1169–1227","1174–1234":"1174–1234","1151–Female":"